>[Question]
>Biff has a choice of 6 items to put on a hamburger. He can only put 
>three items on at a time. These items are ketchup, mustard, relish, 
>mayo, onions, and special sauce. How many different groups of items 
>can he put on his hamburger?


Number of combinations of 3 items chosen from 6 different items

   
  = C(6,3) = 20

                           6 x 5 x 4
This is calculated from   -----------  =  20
                           1 x 2 x 3


>
>[Difficulty]
>What is the formula?
>
>[Thoughts]
>I think the answer is 6x3=18 different groups of items.


